00:37:41.936 --> 00:37:44.530
LORI MCCREARY: Well, I
have a lot of favorites.

00:37:44.530 --> 00:37:46.200
What I just recently
finished watching

00:37:46.200 --> 00:37:48.120
was season 1 of
"Handmaid's Tale."

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:48.909
ALAN SEALES: Mm.

00:37:48.909 --> 00:37:50.450
LORI MCCREARY: Did
you guys see that?

00:37:50.450 --> 00:37:51.230
Oh.

00:37:51.230 --> 00:37:51.880
Yeah.

00:37:51.880 --> 00:37:54.000
Intense, and I couldn't
stop watching it.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:54.750
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:37:54.750 --> 00:37:55.470
Very good.

00:37:55.470 --> 00:37:56.140
MORGAN FREEMAN: All right?

00:37:56.140 --> 00:37:56.450
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:37:56.450 --> 00:37:56.755
LORI MCCREARY: Thanks.

00:37:56.755 --> 00:37:58.350
ALAN SEALES: Yeah,
question over here.

00:37:58.350 --> 00:37:59.850
AUDIENCE: Do you
license your voices

00:37:59.850 --> 00:38:01.500
for use in
text-to-speech engines?

00:38:01.500 --> 00:38:02.000
Like--

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:04.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:04.020 --> 00:38:05.240
--Google Assistant.

00:38:05.240 --> 00:38:07.865
LORI MCCREARY: He wants to know
if you would license your voice

00:38:07.865 --> 00:38:10.741
to use in a
text-to-speech engine.

00:38:10.741 --> 00:38:11.740
MORGAN FREEMAN: Depends.

00:38:11.740 --> 00:38:13.180
LORI MCCREARY: It depends.

00:38:13.180 --> 00:38:14.930
ALAN SEALES: He works
on Google Assistant.

00:38:14.930 --> 00:38:15.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:15.500 --> 00:38:16.666
MORGAN FREEMAN: Oh, does he?

00:38:16.666 --> 00:38:17.625
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:38:17.625 --> 00:38:19.874
MORGAN FREEMAN: Well, I got
to tell you, that depends.

00:38:19.874 --> 00:38:21.089
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:21.089 --> 00:38:22.630
AUDIENCE: If you
want to sound smart,

00:38:22.630 --> 00:38:24.570
you want to be the voice of
Assistant, not the other guys.

00:38:24.570 --> 00:38:25.653
MORGAN FREEMAN: Oh really?

00:38:25.653 --> 00:38:27.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:27.150 --> 00:38:28.602
OK.

00:38:28.602 --> 00:38:29.560
We can talk about that.

00:38:29.560 --> 00:38:32.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:32.550 --> 00:38:34.050
ALAN SEALES: I
actually was planning

00:38:34.050 --> 00:38:36.346
on giving you the Google
Play terms and conditions,

00:38:36.346 --> 00:38:38.220
and just having you read
that for 30 minutes,

00:38:38.220 --> 00:38:39.719
but then I actually
wrote questions.

00:38:39.719 --> 00:38:41.000
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.410
Because we would have
all listened to that too.

00:38:43.410 --> 00:38:44.207
Yeah?

00:38:44.207 --> 00:38:46.290
AUDIENCE: So I was just
wondering, how, if at all,

00:38:46.290 --> 00:38:48.540
did the results of the
presidential election

00:38:48.540 --> 00:38:51.210
last year change the
way you were envisioning

00:38:51.210 --> 00:38:53.202
the development of
the plot for this show

00:38:53.202 --> 00:38:54.285
over the next few seasons?

00:38:57.180 --> 00:39:00.750
MORGAN FREEMAN: You know,
you watch something like that

00:39:00.750 --> 00:39:06.360
and ask yourselves,
can we use it?

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:10.012
The answer is a universal no.

00:39:10.012 --> 00:39:12.220
LORI MCCREARY: I mean, the
good news for us, I think,

00:39:12.220 --> 00:39:14.290
was we started the
show three years

00:39:14.290 --> 00:39:15.980
before the
presidential election.

00:39:15.980 --> 00:39:20.050
So we imagined we'd started the
show two election cycles ahead

00:39:20.050 --> 00:39:21.520
of where we were then currently.

00:39:21.520 --> 00:39:25.360
So in our world, the current
administration never existed.

00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:29.410
So we choose to look at our show
as a more aspirational version

00:39:29.410 --> 00:39:31.660
of maybe what we're seeing
in real life right now,

00:39:31.660 --> 00:39:32.620
and we try to--

00:39:32.620 --> 00:39:34.969
we try to create something
that on Sunday nights,

00:39:34.969 --> 00:39:36.760
you could watch, feel
good about the world,

00:39:36.760 --> 00:39:38.185
and sleep a little better.

00:39:38.185 --> 00:39:40.165
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:40.165 --> 00:39:41.557
[APPLAUSE]

00:39:41.557 --> 00:39:42.640
MORGAN FREEMAN: Well done.

00:39:45.178 --> 00:39:46.886
ALAN SEALES: Do you
have anything to add?

00:39:46.886 --> 00:39:47.820
No?

00:39:47.820 --> 00:39:48.630
MORGAN FREEMAN: No.

00:39:48.630 --> 00:39:48.940
ALAN SEALES: Sweet.

00:39:48.940 --> 00:39:49.440
All right.

00:39:49.440 --> 00:39:50.481
Two more quick questions.

00:39:50.481 --> 00:39:51.090
Yeah?

00:39:51.090 --> 00:39:52.135
AUDIENCE: Hi Morgan.

00:39:52.135 --> 00:39:52.570
MORGAN FREEMAN: Hi.

00:39:52.570 --> 00:39:53.611
AUDIENCE: My name is Fez.

00:39:53.611 --> 00:39:56.590
And you clearly have
such a celebrated career

00:39:56.590 --> 00:39:59.410
with so many different roles
that people recognize you for,

00:39:59.410 --> 00:40:00.550
right?

00:40:00.550 --> 00:40:04.840
I can't think of any other
voice or character that's

00:40:04.840 --> 00:40:09.590
been associated with God as much
or as frequently as you have.

00:40:09.590 --> 00:40:11.169
How does that feel?

00:40:11.169 --> 00:40:11.960
Is that empowering?

00:40:11.960 --> 00:40:14.140
Is that strange?

00:40:14.140 --> 00:40:16.820
Do people come up to
you, asking about that?

00:40:16.820 --> 00:40:17.875
Or am I the first--

00:40:17.875 --> 00:40:19.117
the guy asking this question.

00:40:19.117 --> 00:40:20.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:20.610 --> 00:40:22.680
MORGAN FREEMAN: It's
gotten to be a PITA.

00:40:22.680 --> 00:40:24.130
LORI MCCREARY: A what?

00:40:24.130 --> 00:40:25.446
MORGAN FREEMAN: PITA.

00:40:25.446 --> 00:40:26.612
LORI MCCREARY: Pain in the--

00:40:26.612 --> 00:40:27.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:27.300 --> 00:40:28.425
MORGAN FREEMAN: You got it.

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:37.940
It's terrible to be
so closely associated

00:40:37.940 --> 00:40:44.960
with the idea of God.

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:52.030
It tends to reduce the
importance of the idea of God,

00:40:52.030 --> 00:41:00.670
to walk around saying, this
guy reminds you, you know?

00:41:00.670 --> 00:41:03.040
I'd rather not.

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:04.960
Here again, we're
talking about something

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:06.482
that's good on one
side and really,

00:41:06.482 --> 00:41:07.690
really bad on the other side.

00:41:10.750 --> 00:41:13.720
You like getting recognition
for the work that you've done,

00:41:13.720 --> 00:41:21.070
but some of it's a
little over the top.

00:41:21.070 --> 00:41:21.645
OK?

00:41:21.645 --> 00:41:22.270
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:41:22.270 --> 00:41:24.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:24.010 --> 00:41:24.760
ALAN SEALES: Cool.

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:25.259
Yes.

00:41:25.259 --> 00:41:25.849
Last question.

00:41:25.849 --> 00:41:27.390
AUDIENCE: I'm a huge
fan of the show,

00:41:27.390 --> 00:41:29.750
so thank you so much for coming.

00:41:29.750 --> 00:41:33.115
And since starting to watch
it, I have cut my cord

00:41:33.115 --> 00:41:34.660
and I don't have cable, right?

00:41:34.660 --> 00:41:36.770
So it's the world of
Netflix, world of Hulu.

00:41:36.770 --> 00:41:39.790
CBS is on its own.

00:41:39.790 --> 00:41:41.900
So I just wondered,
as creators--

00:41:41.900 --> 00:41:43.690
and you mentioned
film friends are

00:41:43.690 --> 00:41:46.480
moving on to this TV world--

00:41:46.480 --> 00:41:49.026
as creators, how are you--

00:41:49.026 --> 00:41:50.650
how do you feel about
this whole thing?

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:54.340
Like, how do you feel about CBS
being separate from the others?

00:41:54.340 --> 00:41:57.500
And does it disappoint you, or
is it exciting, and how do you

00:41:57.500 --> 00:41:58.359
feel?

00:41:58.359 --> 00:42:00.400
LORI MCCREARY: You want
to go, or you want me to?

00:42:00.400 --> 00:42:00.760
MORGAN FREEMAN: No.

00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:02.551
I don't even know what
we're talking about.

00:42:02.551 --> 00:42:03.461
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:03.461 --> 00:42:05.710
LORI MCCREARY: She was asking,
because a lot of people

00:42:05.710 --> 00:42:08.530
are cutting their cords,
they either don't have CBS

00:42:08.530 --> 00:42:10.930
or you have to subscribe
to CBS All Access

00:42:10.930 --> 00:42:12.190
to see "Madam Secretary."

00:42:12.190 --> 00:42:14.314
It's not yet on Netflix.

00:42:14.314 --> 00:42:15.730
There was just
announced last week

00:42:15.730 --> 00:42:17.580
that Netflix just did
a big deal with us,

00:42:17.580 --> 00:42:20.110
so that's the good news.

00:42:20.110 --> 00:42:22.840
We went into syndication
early, so that's good.

00:42:22.840 --> 00:42:24.580
But personally,
as a filmmaker, I

00:42:24.580 --> 00:42:26.080
love the fact that
there are so many

00:42:26.080 --> 00:42:30.490
places that we can
create content for.

00:42:30.490 --> 00:42:33.700
So I think it allows more
people to get-- it used

00:42:33.700 --> 00:42:35.050
to be you had seven places.

00:42:35.050 --> 00:42:37.927
If you were a filmmaker, you
had to go to those seven places.

00:42:37.927 --> 00:42:39.510
You had to know
someone there, and you

00:42:39.510 --> 00:42:41.920
had to kind of get
funneled into these places.

00:42:41.920 --> 00:42:43.840
There are hundreds
of places now.

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:47.050
And quite frankly, you
can make your own content

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:48.280
and put it on the internet.

00:42:48.280 --> 00:42:50.230
So we love it.

00:42:50.230 --> 00:42:52.630
We've been a big
proponent of people

00:42:52.630 --> 00:42:55.240
being able to access
content any time, any place.

00:42:55.240 --> 00:42:58.480
I would love it if our
films and our TV content

00:42:58.480 --> 00:43:01.040
are more accessible to everyone.

00:43:01.040 --> 00:43:03.790
It's going to take a while,
because it's all still flushing

00:43:03.790 --> 00:43:05.710
out and people have
business models.

00:43:05.710 --> 00:43:07.506
Like, CBS has a
business model, and they

00:43:07.506 --> 00:43:09.130
know what they're
going to make and how

00:43:09.130 --> 00:43:10.171
they're going to make it.

00:43:10.171 --> 00:43:12.875
And if you break it
up, it's going to--

00:43:12.875 --> 00:43:14.739
if you break up, like,
network television,

00:43:14.739 --> 00:43:16.030
it could break the whole thing.

00:43:16.030 --> 00:43:17.350
So they're doing it slowly.

00:43:17.350 --> 00:43:21.240
And CBS is one of the first to
have their own CBS All Access.

00:43:21.240 --> 00:43:23.290
So I applaud them
for dipping their toe

00:43:23.290 --> 00:43:25.240
in before some of the others.

00:43:25.240 --> 00:43:28.875
And I'm just-- I'm just
excited to see what's next.

00:43:28.875 --> 00:43:30.708
MORGAN FREEMAN: You
know why she's so smart?

00:43:30.708 --> 00:43:31.524
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:32.340 --> 00:43:37.387
She had a-- has an
outstanding set of parents.

00:43:37.387 --> 00:43:38.220
LORI MCCREARY: I do.

00:43:38.220 --> 00:43:43.086
MORGAN FREEMAN:
Really created her.

00:43:43.086 --> 00:43:44.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:44.960 --> 00:43:46.025
ALAN SEALES: Literally?

00:43:46.025 --> 00:43:46.310
MORGAN FREEMAN: Yeah.

00:43:46.310 --> 00:43:46.670
ALAN SEALES: Yes.

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:47.120
LORI MCCREARY: Literally.

00:43:47.120 --> 00:43:47.510
MORGAN FREEMAN: Yeah.

00:43:47.510 --> 00:43:48.468
ALAN SEALES: All right.

00:43:48.468 --> 00:43:50.360
So last question from me.

00:43:50.360 --> 00:43:52.210
Looking back on your
careers, both of you,

00:43:52.210 --> 00:43:55.331
is there a single
defining moment

00:43:55.331 --> 00:43:56.810
that you can look
at and say, this

00:43:56.810 --> 00:44:00.560
is why I am today,
because of that moment?

00:44:00.560 --> 00:44:02.590
MORGAN FREEMAN: Yeah.

00:44:02.590 --> 00:44:04.796
Yeah.

00:44:04.796 --> 00:44:06.670
When I was 12 years old,
I pulled a chair out

00:44:06.670 --> 00:44:07.590
from under a girl.

00:44:07.590 --> 00:44:10.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:11.080 --> 00:44:14.870
And she chased me.

00:44:14.870 --> 00:44:16.620
I thought she was
really going to kill me.

00:44:16.620 --> 00:44:18.344
[LAUGH]

00:44:19.210 --> 00:44:24.480
And I was collared by an English
teacher who frogmarched me

00:44:24.480 --> 00:44:28.680
down a hall and shoved me into
a room and said, here he is.

00:44:28.680 --> 00:44:31.430
And that was my
first opportunity

00:44:31.430 --> 00:44:34.192
at getting on stage as an actor.

00:44:34.192 --> 00:44:37.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:37.290 --> 00:44:38.880
ALAN SEALES: And you enjoyed it?

00:44:38.880 --> 00:44:39.990
MORGAN FREEMAN: Immensely.

00:44:39.990 --> 00:44:41.910
I got my first best actor award.

00:44:41.910 --> 00:44:44.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:44.120 --> 00:44:46.007
ALAN SEALES: Detention?

00:44:46.007 --> 00:44:47.090
MORGAN FREEMAN: Detention?

00:44:47.090 --> 00:44:49.548
ALAN SEALES: For pulling the
chair out from under the girl?

00:44:49.548 --> 00:44:51.640
MORGAN FREEMAN: Well,
I tell that story now,

00:44:51.640 --> 00:44:54.371
and she was at my 80th
birthday party, grinning.

00:44:54.371 --> 00:44:56.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:56.680 --> 00:44:58.050
ALAN SEALES: That's funny.

00:44:58.050 --> 00:44:59.419
Lori, do you have a moment?

00:44:59.419 --> 00:45:01.710
LORI MCCREARY: I honestly--
not just because he's here.

00:45:01.710 --> 00:45:05.290
I think meeting Morgan was the
defining moment in my career.

00:45:05.290 --> 00:45:06.180
I came from--

00:45:06.180 --> 00:45:09.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:10.980
--I was making my first movie.

00:45:10.980 --> 00:45:13.620
I didn't know if it's
what I was going to be

00:45:13.620 --> 00:45:14.760
doing the rest of my life.

00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:19.470
And And thankfully,
when we connected,

00:45:19.470 --> 00:45:21.924
I immediately got
something that is

00:45:21.924 --> 00:45:23.340
hard to get in our
business, which

00:45:23.340 --> 00:45:26.880
is when I walked into a room,
he, even if he wasn't there,

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:27.960
walked in before me.

00:45:27.960 --> 00:45:32.400
So people automatically gave
me more credit for being smart,

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:35.310
full of integrity, everything
you see this man is.

00:45:35.310 --> 00:45:36.362
And so I've been able--

00:45:36.362 --> 00:45:37.695
MORGAN FREEMAN: Not bad looking.

00:45:37.695 --> 00:45:37.980
LORI MCCREARY: Yeah.

00:45:37.980 --> 00:45:38.521
Good looking.

00:45:38.521 --> 00:45:41.258
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:41.258 --> 00:45:44.295
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:44.295 --> 00:45:46.564
So I would credit
connecting with Mr. Freeman.

00:45:46.564 --> 00:45:47.730
ALAN SEALES: That's amazing.

00:45:47.730 --> 00:45:48.520
Well, thank you both for being--

00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:50.186
MORGAN FREEMAN: Did
you write that down?

00:45:50.186 --> 00:45:51.042
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:51.042 --> 00:45:53.000
ALAN SEALES: It's now
out there on Googleverse.

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:53.240
MORGAN FREEMAN: OK.

00:45:53.240 --> 00:45:54.870
ALAN SEALES: The
Googleverse, yes.

00:45:54.870 --> 00:45:57.390
Yeah, so you can follow
Lori McCreary on Twitter

00:45:57.390 --> 00:45:59.080
@LoriMcCreary.

00:45:59.080 --> 00:46:00.330
Morgan, you aren't on Twitter.

00:46:00.330 --> 00:46:01.205
MORGAN FREEMAN: Nope.

00:46:01.205 --> 00:46:02.080
ALAN SEALES: Nope.

